    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-1376" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01493708300940204826" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2005/04/9-am-sunday-bubbling-oil-and-beignets/#comment-1376"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2005-04-20T03:35:00-04:00">Wednesday, April 20, 2005 at 3:35 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Tara, you&#8217;ve got it exactly right.  The beignets were miraculously both decadent and light!  Jimmy is truly a master.  But now that you&#8217;ve got the recipe, mastery will soon be yours as well!  Oh, and very glad to hear about the asparagus&#8230;I have a few spears waiting in my fridge right now, actually.  Yum.</></>Sammy, sorry to hear that.  I suppose you&#8217;ve learned your lesson, though?</></>And Rebecca, dear, you are always too too, just too much!  I can hardly wait until next Sunday&#8211;although without any sugar, whatever will I write about?  Oh, and WHEN is my manicure?  I know how you feel about my cuticles.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-1377" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Anonymous</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2005/04/9-am-sunday-bubbling-oil-and-beignets/#comment-1377"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2005-04-23T13:34:00-04:00">Saturday, April 23, 2005 at 1:34 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Oh, shame on me! It must be my Mexican-Jewish background, but we make these, sometimes yeast-risen, sometimes baking-powder-risen, and while they&#8217;r hot, bite a corner off and pour honey into them. Honey, powdered sugar &#8211; it&#8217;s still a sugar rush.</></>Your Unc from Maine.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-1378" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01493708300940204826" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2005/04/9-am-sunday-bubbling-oil-and-beignets/#comment-1378"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2005-04-23T15:58:00-04:00">Saturday, April 23, 2005 at 3:58 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>My dear Unc., those (sopaipillas, yes?) sound delicious.  Though honey might well be blasphemy to Rebecca and Jimmy, I could be talked into it&#8230;</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-1379" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://www.afrolicofmyown.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Frolic</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2005/04/9-am-sunday-bubbling-oil-and-beignets/#comment-1379"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2005-05-09T14:25:00-04:00">Monday, May 9, 2005 at 2:25 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Looks like you did these right, but I&#8217;m just mystified by all this talk of &#8220;shame.&#8221; Lighten up! This is a New Orleans dish. The entire city would grind to a halt if we worried much about &#8220;shame.&#8221;</></>And don&#8217;t listen to your friend about the proper way to eat beignets. In my experience, beignets are best eaten early in the morning when an out-of-town visitor has dragged you to Bourbon Street. You can&#8217;t walk through Bourbon Street without ruining a pair a shoes and permanently staining the cuffs of your pants. A little powdered sugar is the least of your cleaning concerns.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-1380" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01493708300940204826" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2005/04/9-am-sunday-bubbling-oil-and-beignets/#comment-1380"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2005-05-11T01:38:00-04:00">Wednesday, May 11, 2005 at 1:38 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Frolic, thank you for helping me learn to stop worrying and love my powdered-sugared pants.  You&#8217;re right: shame is highly overrated!  Come to think of it, I&#8217;m surprised that the word is even in Rebecca&#8217;s vocabulary&#8230;</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-1381" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Lauren</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2005/04/9-am-sunday-bubbling-oil-and-beignets/#comment-1381"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2009-04-04T23:02:00-04:00">Saturday, April 4, 2009 at 11:02 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>These look and sound fantastic! Just a question, do you let the dough come to room temp after its overnight proof/allow it a second proof before frying?</>Can&#8217;t wait to make them 🙂</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-1382" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01493708300940204826" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2005/04/9-am-sunday-bubbling-oil-and-beignets/#comment-1382"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2009-04-05T02:25:00-04:00">Sunday, April 5, 2009 at 2:25 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Lauren, I&#8217;m not sure what to tell you!  I got this recipe from Jimmy and haven&#8217;t made them myself, so I&#8217;m not sure if you should let the dough come to room temperature / do a second proof before frying.  If I were you, I might look up other beignet recipes and see what they say.  Sorry I can&#8217;t be more helpful&#8230;</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    </ol>

      
  
